  ]}
  relatedApplications={[
    { label: "Oil Centrifuge Applications", href: "/oil-centrifuge/" },
    { label: "Disc Stack Centrifuge FAQ", href: "/disc-stack-centrifuge-faq/" },
    { label: "Disc Centrifuge Backpressure Guide", href: "/disc-centrifuge-backpressure/" },
    { label: "Fluid Heating Systems", href: "/fluid-heating-systems/" },
  ]}
>

  <!-- AI Summary -->
  <div class="bg-navy/5 border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg p-4 mb-6">
    <p class="text-sm text-text-light leading-relaxed italic">Dolphin Centrifuge designs and supplies disc stack centrifuge accessories including electric preheaters, pre-filters with 1 mm disc-clearance protection, sludge handling systems, flow meters, heat recovery modules, and PLC automation panels — all factory-integrated into complete skid systems and tested before shipment.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-10">
    <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">The end-user can implement disc centrifuge accessories to enhance centrifuge performance by conditioning the process fluid, improving ease of operation, and managing centrifuge effluent. In this article, we discuss the various disc centrifuge accessories and their benefits. It is important to note that these centrifuge accessories are suitable for all <a href="/industrial-centrifuge/" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">industrial centrifuges</a>.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Fluid Pre-Heating System -->
  <h2 id="fluid-preheating" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Fluid Pre-Heating System</h2>
  <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
    <div class="space-y-4 text-text-light">

      <img
        src="/images/alfa-laval-disc-centrifuge-accessories/Heater-Pump-Filter-Skid.webp"
        alt="Dolphin Centrifuge Electric Pre-Heater skid for disc centrifuge systems"
        width="600" height="600"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg w-full mb-4"
      />
      <p class="text-sm text-center text-gray-500 -mt-2 mb-4 italic">Dolphin Centrifuge's Electric Pre-Heater</p>

      <p>A disc centrifuge is often used as an <a href="/oil-centrifuge/" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">oil centrifuge</a> to separate water and solid contaminants from the oil. One of the process liquid properties that influences the centrifuge separation efficiency is the oil's viscosity.</p>
      <p>As shown in the graph below, the viscosity of an oil is inversely proportional to its temperature. So it is essential to process hot oil through a centrifuge for best results.</p>

      <img
        src="/images/alfa-laval-disc-centrifuge-accessories/oil-viscosity-vs-temperature-600.webp"
        alt="Oil Viscosity versus Temperature graph showing how viscosity drops as temperature rises"
        width="600" height="400"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg w-full my-4"
      />
      <p class="text-sm text-center text-gray-500 -mt-2 mb-4 italic">Oil Viscosity versus Temperature Graph</p>

      <p>It is easy to integrate an oil preheating system into a disc centrifuge module. Apart from the benefit of centrifuging hot oil, a centrifuge oil heating system is much more efficient than heating the oil in the storage tank. Heated oil storage tanks lose most of the heat to the environment and are therefore not energy-efficient or environmentally responsible.</p>
      <p>The following are some of the options for preheating the process fluid before centrifugation.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-navy mt-4">Electric Heating</h3>
      <p>The most straightforward and convenient oil preheater is of the electrical type. A circulation-type electric heater heats the process fluid before it enters the centrifuge. The primary benefit of this design is that it heats only the fluid in circulation and not the entire storage tank volume. Therefore, this type of preheating system is highly efficient.</p>
      <p>Electric oil heating systems have digital temperature monitoring systems, overheat shutoff, automatic or manual bypass valve manifolds, etc.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-navy mt-4">Steam Heating</h3>
      <p>Although steam heating systems are pretty inefficient, they are popular due to their simplicity and the availability of steam at existing plants. A simple, off-the-shelf heat exchanger uses steam to heat the fluid before the centrifuge.</p>
      <p>The heat exchanger is susceptible to clogging or blockage from the process fluid if the fluid has significant sludge content. The sludge tends to settle out within the heat exchanger over time and reduces the efficiency and flow rate of the system.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-navy mt-4">Special Non-Clogging Heat Exchanger</h3>

      <img
        src="/images/alfa-laval-disc-centrifuge-accessories/centrifuge-fluid-heating-loop.webp"
        alt="Fluid heating system for industrial disc centrifuge with pipe-in-pipe heat loop design"
        width="600" height="458"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg w-full my-4"
      />
      <p class="text-sm text-center text-gray-500 -mt-2 mb-4 italic">Fluid Heating System for Disc Centrifuge</p>

      <p>Dolphin Centrifuge has developed a proprietary pipe-in-pipe heat loop system for efficient heating of process fluids before centrifugation. The design of these heat loops centers around ease of cleaning and the ability to use steam or heat transfer fluid as the heating medium.</p>
      <p>These heat loops are perfect for preheating process fluids with a large proportion of sludge.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Filters or Strainers -->
  <h2 id="filters-strainers" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Filters or Strainers</h2>
  <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
    <div class="space-y-4 text-text-light">
      <p>Depending on the application, filters play an essential role in centrifuge performance and optimization. Filters upstream and downstream of the centrifuge serve different purposes. The industry refers to the upstream filters as pre-filters, and the downstream filters are known as post or polishing filters.</p>

      <img
        src="/images/alfa-laval-disc-centrifuge-accessories/product_prestainerskid.webp"
        alt="Dolphin Centrifuge Pre-Strainer System with Electric Heater for disc centrifuge"
        width="600" height="600"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg w-full my-4"
      />
      <p class="text-sm text-center text-gray-500 -mt-2 mb-4 italic">Dolphin Centrifuge's Pre-Strainer System with Electric Heater</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-navy mt-4">Pre-Filters</h3>
      <p>A <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge/" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">disc stack centrifuge</a> has an inherent limitation on the maximum particle size the centrifuge can accept. This limitation is due to the inter disc spacing of the disc stack. Typically, the discs have a clearance of 1 mm between them.</p>
      <p>Large particles can get wedged between the discs and block the fluid passing through the discs. Therefore, it is essential to pre-strain the process fluid before entering the centrifuge to keep the large particles out. A pre-filter or inline strainer prevents such large particles from entering the centrifuge.</p>

      <img
        src="/images/alfa-laval-disc-centrifuge-accessories/stainless-steel-filters.webp"
        alt="Stainless steel disc centrifuge pre-filters for particle protection"
        width="487" height="238"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg w-full my-4"
      />
      <p class="text-sm text-center text-gray-500 -mt-2 mb-4 italic">Disc Centrifuge Pre-Filters</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-navy mt-4">Post Filters (Polishing Filters)</h3>
      <p>Post or polishing filters provide absolute filtration after the centrifuge. In other words, disc centrifuges are mechanical separating machines that separate the particles by the magnified force of gravity. Though these centrifuges are powerful enough to separate particles as small as 1 micron, some large particles can pass through the centrifuge for various reasons, such as high flow rate or centrifuge malfunction.</p>
      <p>A post or polishing filter catches any stray particles that escape the centrifuge and thus ensures the centrate meets the specified purity level.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Sludge Handling System -->
  <h2 id="sludge-handling" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Sludge Handling System</h2>
  <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
    <div class="space-y-4 text-text-light">
      <p>The separated sludge from a disc stack centrifuge falls out under gravity from the centrifuge frame sludge chute. Most centrifuges have the sludge discharge chute oriented downward.</p>
      <p>The two main options for installing a self-cleaning disc stack centrifuge are installing the centrifuge on an elevated platform to place a sludge receptacle below the centrifuge, or integrating a sludge collection and transfer sub-system as part of the centrifuge module.</p>
      <p>The second option offers the benefit of the centrifuge module being moveable and not anchored to the floor. This option also eliminates the requirement of constructing an elevated platform on site.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-navy mt-4">Sludge Tank</h3>
      <p>The optimum design for a system-integrated sludge tank is to install a centrifuge on top of a structural tank that receives the falling sludge ejection from the centrifuge.</p>
      <p>The sludge tank is a welded steel box structure with a sloping bottom. The sludge slurry accumulates in the tank towards the sloped end.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-navy mt-4">Sludge Transfer Pump</h3>
      <p>The disc centrifuge ejects the separated sludge as a thick slurry. An air-operated double-diaphragm (AODD) pump is best suited for pumping this slurry.</p>
      <p>The sludge handling system integrates an AODD pump automatically activated by a level sensor or a level switch inside the sludge tank.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-navy mt-4">Tank Heater</h3>
      <p>The separated sludge from crude oil, bunker fuel, and other similar thick fluids is very viscous. Once it accumulates in the sludge tank, this sludge often solidifies and is no longer pumpable.</p>
      <p>A sludge tank heater keeps the separated sludge at a higher temperature, keeping it in a pumpable state. Sludge tank heaters are electric heating elements inside the tank that remain submerged in the sludge. These heating elements are temperature-controlled and automatically activated based on the sludge level in the tank.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Flow Meter & Totalizer -->
  <h2 id="flow-meter" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Flow Meter &amp; Totalizer</h2>
  <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
    <div class="space-y-4 text-text-light">

      <img
        src="/images/alfa-laval-disc-centrifuge-accessories/Centrifuge-Flow-Meter-600.webp"
        alt="Centrifuge flow meter for monitoring process fluid flow rate into the centrifuge"
        width="600" height="221"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg w-full my-4"
      />
      <p class="text-sm text-center text-gray-500 -mt-2 mb-4 italic">Centrifuge Flow Meter</p>

      <p>A flow meter or totalizer is an inline flow measuring device that monitors the fluid flow into the centrifuge. The actual flow rate is a crucial parameter in the operation of a self-cleaning disc stack centrifuge.</p>
      <p>The sludge discharge cycle period depends on the percentage of solids and the flow rate of the fluid. An accurate discharge cycle period is essential for the centrifuge to operate in high-efficiency mode.</p>
      <p>When integrated into the centrifuge control system, the totalizer records the total batch volume processed by the centrifuge.</p>
      <p>Mechanical, turbine-type flow indicators let the centrifuge operator know the actual flow rate of the process fluid and, therefore, calculate the appropriate sludge cycle time.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Clean Fluid Handling System -->
  <h2 id="clean-fluid" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Clean Fluid Handling System</h2>
  <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
    <div class="space-y-4 text-text-light">

      <img
        src="/images/alfa-laval-disc-centrifuge-accessories/Alfa-Laval-MAPX210-Diesel-Skid.webp"
        alt="Disc centrifuge system with clean fluid collection tank and transfer pump"
        width="600" height="600"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg w-full my-4"
      />
      <p class="text-sm text-center text-gray-500 -mt-2 mb-4 italic">Disc Centrifuge With Clean Fluid Tank</p>

      <p>The disc centrifuge discharges the clean centrate under pressure. However, the operator should not use this pressure to transfer the fluid over long distances or to exert excessive backpressure on the centrifuge. A local clean fluid collection tank is an excellent solution to alleviate this problem.</p>
      <p>A local, skid-mounted, clean fluid tank with a transfer pump is a popular optional accessory for a disc stack centrifuge system. The clean fluid transfers to this tank with the centrifuge-generated pressure with negligible backpressure.</p>
      <p>The level sensor on the clean fluid tank activates the transfer pump, which transfers the fluid to remote storage tanks.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Chemical Injection & Mixing System -->
  <h2 id="chemical-injection" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Chemical Injection &amp; Mixing System</h2>
  <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
    <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
      <p>Some applications such as emulsified oil or crude oil require chemical additives or flocculants to assist in the separation of the fluid phases. A chemical injection port on the inlet side piping of the centrifuge system facilitates introducing the chemical to the flow stream.</p>
      <p>The operator can dial in a chemical metering pump to supply the correct amount of additive into the process stream.</p>
      <p>A high-shear, inline, static mixer vigorously mixes the chemical into the process fluid before the fluid enters the centrifuge. This system eliminates the need to add chemicals to the supply tank and avoids related wastage of chemicals.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Heat Recovery Module -->
  <h2 id="heat-recovery" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Heat Recovery Module</h2>
  <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
    <div class="space-y-4 text-text-light">

      <img
        src="/images/alfa-laval-disc-centrifuge-accessories/Disc-Centrifuge-Accessories-Heat-Recovery-Skid-600.webp"
        alt="Disc centrifuge accessories heat recovery skid with plate and frame heat exchanger"
        width="450" height="395"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg w-full my-4"
      />
      <p class="text-sm text-center text-gray-500 -mt-2 mb-4 italic">Disc Centrifuge Accessories — Heat Recovery Skid</p>

      <p>Large volume applications such as crude oil dewatering require large amounts of energy to heat the crude oil before centrifugation. The separated water and oil phases exiting the centrifuge have thermic energy that the users typically waste in the storage tanks.</p>
      <p>A heat recovery system is essentially a plate and frame heat exchanger that uses the heat from the clean fluid leaving the centrifuge to heat the incoming, unprocessed fluid. Such an accessory can lead to considerable energy savings.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Feed Pumps -->
  <h2 id="feed-pumps" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Feed Pumps</h2>
  <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-6">
    <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
      <p>The feed pump delivers process fluid to the centrifuge inlet at the correct pressure and flow rate. Centrifuge bowls are designed for a specific feed pressure range — too high causes overflow and product loss; too low starves the disc stack and reduces separation efficiency. The pump type must be matched to the fluid viscosity, temperature, and required flow rate.</p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 text-sm mt-4">
        <div>
          <p class="font-bold text-navy mb-2">Pump Types</p>
          <ul class="space-y-1">
            <li>&bull; Gear pumps — viscous oils, positive displacement</li>
            <li>&bull; Centrifugal pumps — water-based and low-viscosity fluids</li>
            <li>&bull; Progressive cavity pumps — highly viscous or shear-sensitive feeds</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="font-bold text-navy mb-2">Selection Criteria</p>
          <ul class="space-y-1">
            <li>&bull; All centrifuge installations (gravity feed is rarely sufficient)</li>
            <li>&bull; Match viscous fluids to positive displacement type</li>
            <li>&bull; Systems where pressure must be regulated precisely</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Back Pressure Regulators -->
  <h2 id="back-pressure" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Back Pressure Regulators</h2>
  <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-6">
    <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
      <p>Back pressure regulators (BPRs) maintain a controlled, positive pressure at the centrifuge outlet. This is critical for hermetically sealed (pressure-tight) disc stack centrifuges where maintaining the liquid seal inside the bowl is essential for separation. A BPR ensures the bowl never operates with a partially flooded or air-filled interior.</p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 text-sm mt-4">
        <div>
          <p class="font-bold text-navy mb-2">Typical Settings</p>
          <ul class="space-y-1">
            <li>&bull; Light phase outlet: 0.5–2.5 bar</li>
            <li>&bull; Heavy phase outlet: 0.3–1.5 bar</li>
            <li>&bull; Settings depend on model and application</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="font-bold text-navy mb-2">When Required</p>
          <ul class="space-y-1">
            <li>&bull; All hermetic (pressure-tight) disc stack models</li>
            <li>&bull; Volatile fluids where flashing at the outlet could occur</li>
            <li>&bull; Systems where outlet piping runs uphill</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- PLC Controls -->
  <h2 id="plc-controls" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">PLC Controls &amp; Automation Panels</h2>
  <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-6">
    <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
      <p>Modern disc stack centrifuges can be integrated with PLC-based automation panels that manage startup, shutdown, discharge sequencing, alarm handling, and remote monitoring. A well-configured control system eliminates manual operator intervention, optimizes discharge intervals based on real-time data, and protects the machine from dangerous operating conditions.</p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 text-sm mt-4">
        <div>
          <p class="font-bold text-navy mb-2">Standard Functions</p>
          <ul class="space-y-1">
            <li>&bull; Automatic startup and speed monitoring</li>
            <li>&bull; Timed discharge sequencing (self-cleaning models)</li>
            <li>&bull; Temperature, pressure, and flow monitoring</li>
            <li>&bull; Vibration and bearing temperature alarms</li>
            <li>&bull; Remote start/stop and Modbus/Ethernet integration</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="font-bold text-navy mb-2">Integration Options</p>
          <ul class="space-y-1">
            <li>&bull; NEC/NFPA standards for US facilities</li>
            <li>&bull; ATEX/IECEx rated panels for hazardous areas</li>
            <li>&bull; HMI touchscreens for operator interface</li>
            <li>&bull; 4–20mA outputs for process historian integration</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm mt-3">See <a href="/industrial-centrifuge-controls/" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">Industrial Centrifuge Controls</a> for more detail on control system options.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Gravity Disc Sets -->
  <h2 id="gravity-discs" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Gravity Disc Sets</h2>
  <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
    <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
      <p>Gravity disc sets include a range of gravity disc sizes matched to the centrifuge model. Each disc controls the liquid–liquid interface position inside the bowl when operating in purifier (three-phase) mode. Different gravity disc sizes are required for fluids of different densities — switching from diesel fuel to transformer oil, for example, typically requires a different gravity disc.</p>
      <p>Sets typically include 5–10 discs of incrementally different inner diameters. A larger bore moves the interface outward (more water phase volume); a smaller bore moves the interface inward (more oil phase volume). Selection charts are available from Dolphin for common oils.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <div id="faq" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mt-8 mb-6">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What accessories does Dolphin Centrifuge supply for disc stack centrifuges?</h3>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Dolphin Centrifuge supplies heater-timer panels for automatic operation scheduling, heating systems (shell-and-tube and electric), sludge collection tanks, feed pumps, pre-filter assemblies, flow meters, and complete PLC control panels with touchscreen interfaces. All accessories are integrated into complete centrifuge system packages.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What is a heater-timer panel used for on a centrifuge?</h3>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm">A heater-timer panel controls the on/off timing and feed fluid temperature for automatic centrifuge operation. It allows the centrifuge to start, purify, and shut down automatically on a schedule — maintaining proper feed temperature without manual intervention. This is essential for unattended overnight or weekend operation in industrial facilities.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">Do I need a separate feed pump with a disc centrifuge system?</h3>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Yes, in most installations a dedicated feed pump is required to supply fluid to the centrifuge at the correct pressure and flow rate. Dolphin Centrifuge supplies complete skid packages with integrated pump, heating system, flow controls, and PLC panel — delivered pre-wired and factory tested, ready for field connection.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Related Articles -->
